Jurgis Bekepuris: I haven't a good reason for choosing IFN over IIF. IFN has a
little greater discount to NAV. It's somewhat positive to me that management
has stated they'll have an on-going buyback. That will keep the discount
narrow. OTOH, I want fund monies going into Indian companies shares - that's
why I bought the fund - rather than having management sell shares of those
stocks to to buy IFN shares.

I don't like what I've seen in past about how Morgan Stanley operates in the
closed-end world. (They're IIF's fund manager.) I believe they make their money
by taking a percentage of the assets they manage. So there's an incentive for
adding additional shares to raise more capital and raise the asset base. In
past, I have seen them price offerings of new stock below current price which
in turn might be below NAV. In my limited experience, the result is to bring
the stock price down for current shareholders.

That said, IFN has some concerns for me also. (heavy weighting in one
unknown-to-me stock.) I'm still doing research on IFN (Thanks for the alert
about tax consequences.), and I'll look closer at IIF as well. It's not an
either/or situation for me. Perhaps a position in either or both stocks might
be suitable if one wants an exposure to India.
