Slam Dunks? - From Barron's
by: quietcompany (32/M/New York, NY)
Long-Term Sentiment: Strong Buy
By RHONDA BRAMMER

WHAT A GREAT TIME TO HAVE OWNED small stocks! While the overall market, as
measured by the S&P 500, is ahead a none-too-shabby 17% this year, the S&P
SmallCap 600 and the Russell 2000 -- two proxies for small caps -- are up a
nifty 25% and 32%, respectively. Exciting and rewarding as the run has been, we
must confess we feel a tad antsy. The market has come awfully far, awfully
fast. Little tech outfits bereft of earnings have been bid sky-high. Day
traders and momentum players are back. And, perhaps most unsettling of all, the
investment pros who love small stocks but harbor a keen sense of value -- the
sort of managers we tend to feature in this space -- are lightening up on their
winners and having a devil of a time finding compelling new names to buy.

Which is why we were pleasantly surprised last week when we touched base with
Mitch Sacks, who runs cheekily named Grand Slam Capital Partners. His Fort Lee,
N.J.-based hedge fund is up an awesome 69% through September -- and, yes,
that's net of fees -- but Mitch is still turning up a fetching idea now and
again, though he readily concedes it's a lot tougher than it was six or so
months ago.

And rather than lightening up on two small-cap names he plugged in this space
in May and July -- even though both have since risen by some 30% -- he has been
steadily adding to his stakes. With the economy giving off hints of strength,
Mitch reckons both could come close to doubling from their current levels.

Mentioned in late May at around 10, Johnson Outdoors now trades at 13 and
change, furnishing it with a market cap of around $110 million. The company's
cash is almost equal to its long-term debt, and its shares still sell right
around tangible book.

Controlled by the Johnson family (of Johnson Wax fame), Johnson Outdoors is a
restructuring play that capitalizes on the growing trend of all manner of folks
to seek a more active lifestyle. Last year the company jettisoned an apparel
division so it could focus on higher-tech, faster-growing recreational gear,
markets where it ranks No. 1 or No. 2.

In watercraft, for example, Johnson leads the pack in canoes, kayaks and pedal
boats, with brands such as Old Town, Necky, Leisure Life, Ocean Kayak and
Carlisle. The company is the top player in trolling motors, with its Minn Kota
brand, and No. 2 in diving gear, with names that include Scubapro, Aladin,
SnorkelPro and Uwatec. Johnson also sells camping and military tents -- the
latter, a great biz of late -- under brands such as Eureka!

Back in May, Sacks reckoned that Johnson would earn 90 cents to $1 a share for
fiscal 2003, ended September, compared with 94 cents in September 2002. He now
thinks that for fiscal 2003, exclusive of one-time charges, Johnson will report
$1.25 to $1.30 a share. And for fiscal 2004, he's looking for $1.45-$1.50.

His 12-to-18-month target is north of $25.
