Paul, you made a great point. 10-bagger isn't the only way to make money in
stock market. Prudent value investors often sell after the deeply undervalued
stock reached fair value. There is nothing wrong to do that.

In my 12 years practicing valve investing, I found deeply undervalued (below
cash) quality stocks only appear once in every couple years, in 1997-98
semiconductor slump, or 2002 in Telecom and Biotech. They are all gone now,
well above book value. I do think my 20 years technology industry insight
helped me to identify emerging leaders in growing sectors - and being able to
hold on to the leaders like SINA. My success in founding and growing a computer
business in China, over a decade experience working at world-leading financial
and IT companies in USA, my vast network of contacts in China IT industry (I
was the cover page story on Beijing Daily many years ago, also on China Youth
Daily, etc.) help me get a good pulse of the most dynamic, fast growing economy
- China. I believe if I can maintain a calm attitude, not be carried away by my
success (up 278% since July2001), stay disciplined - no margin, just
long/short, I am on track to a successful investor (and money manager) in this
China decade. There are many great minds over here so I will continue to learn
from all of you, thanks to this greatest thread on SI.

